 Study of Developments in Victoria, Australia -- tEpilogue -- tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGlobal migration continues to increase, and with it comes increasing linguistic diversity. This presents obvious challenges for both healthcare provider and patient, and the chapters in this volume represent a range of international perspectives on language barriers in health care. A variety of factors influence the best ways of approaching and overcoming these language barriers, including cultural, geographical, political and practical considerations, and as a result a range of approaches and solutions are suggested and discussed. The authors in this volume discuss a wide range of countries and languages, and cover issues that will be familiar to all healthcare practitioners, including the role of informal interpreters, interpreting in a clinical setting, bilingual healthcare practitioners and working with languages with comparatively small numbers of speakers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCommunication in medicine. 0aHealth facilitiesxTranslating services. 0aLinguistic minoritiesxMedical care. 0aMedicinexTranslating. 0aTranscultural medical care. 0aTranslating and interpreting. 7aMEDICAL / Physician & Patient.2bisacsh  aLanguage barriers.  ahealth care equity.  ahealth disparities.  ahealth equity.  ahealth policy.  aimmigration.  ainterpreting.  amedical communication.  aphysician patient communication.1 aBoilard, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrisset, Camille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanfield, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiamond, Lisa C., econtributor